<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">36129384</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2022</Year><Month>10</Month><Day>31</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2023</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>02</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1545-5017</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>69</Volume><Issue>12</Issue><PubDate><Year>2022</Year><Month>Dec</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Pediatric blood &amp; cancer</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Pediatr Blood Cancer</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Cure4Kids: Two decades of knowledge transfer.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>e30007</StartPage><MedlinePgn>e30007</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1002/pbc.30007</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>Cure4Kids is a free web-based knowledge platform for professionals providing care for children with cancer and hematologic diseases, offering its users a comprehensive suite of learning opportunities. It has been a resource for the pediatric oncology community across the world for the past two decades, with 60,107 users having logged in 1,412,514 times with 22,045,553 content hits. A transformation of Cure4Kids is being planned and will include an improved user interface, increased interactivity, and more content.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>&#xa9; 2022 Wiley Periodicals LLC.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Moreira</LastName><ForeName>Daniel C</ForeName><Initials>DC</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0003-4082-156X</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Global Pediatric Medicine, St. Jude Children's Research Hospital, Memphis, Tennessee, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Jones</LastName><ForeName>Hannah M</ForeName><Initials>HM</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Texas Tech University